5000|$|On January 21 1955, Schjeldahl {{began making}} {{plans for a}} new company to be located in the {{basement}} of the Medical Arts building in Northfield, Minnesota. The company secured a contract in April 1955 to create atmospheric research balloons made with Mylar polyester film, held together with an adhesive system that Schjeldahl developed. On September 1 1955, the G.T. Schjeldahl Company went public. In addition to balloons, the company manufactured bag-making machines and <b>heat-sealing</b> <b>adhesive</b> tape. Eventually the company began developing a line of adhesive tapes for polyester bonding called Schjel-Bond (GT100, GT200, GT300, and GT400).|$|E

